                  "__cdata": "<p class=\"p_20 black\">Correct!</p><p>Correct answer is C : Sickle cell trait<br/><p><span style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">What is the difference between sickle cell disease and trait? </span></p><p><strong>People with sickle cell trait (AS) </strong>inherit one gene for normal hemoglobin (A) and one gene for sickle hemoglobin (S) from their parents. Because they have one (A) gene, individuals with traits do not have any medical problems, but they can pass the (S) gene to their children. </p><p><strong>People with sickle cell disease (SS) </strong><span style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">inherit two genes for sickle hemoglobin (S) from their parents</span>. They have symptoms because their red blood cells do not make normal hemoglobin. </p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">sickle Trait=T</span> <span style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">sickle Disease =D</span> T-one S gene D-double SS gene T-20-40% of hemoglobin is hemoglobin S D-80-100% is HBS T-do not have any health problem D-no symptoms under normal conditions But in sickling crisis such as infection and dehydration, they get symptoms plus anemia and jaundice.</p><p><br></p><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">The diagnostic test-</strong></p><ul><li>The best initial test is a peripheral smear. Sickle cell trait (AS disease) does not give sickled cells. The most accurate test is hemoglobin electrophoresis.</li><li>Do not wait for the results of testing to start antibiotics if there is a fever. The absence of a functional spleen leads to overwhelming infection.</li><li>Patients with sickle cell disease usually have very high reticulocyte counts because of the chronic compensated hemolysis.</li></ul><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">Treatment of Sickle cell disease</strong></p><p><a href=\"https://emedicine.medscape.com/article/205926-workup#c1\" target=\"_blank\">Sickle Cell Anemia Workup: Approach Considerations, Baseline Blood Study Abnormalities, Suggested Routine Clinical Laboratory Evaluations (medscape.com)</a></p><p>Treatment</p><ul><li>Begin with oxygen/hydration/analgesia. If fever or a white blood cell count higher than usual is present, then antibiotics are given. Use ceftriaxone, levofloxacin, or moxifloxacin.</li><li>Folic acid replacement is necessary on a chronic basis.</li><li>Give pneumococcal vaccination because of auto splenectomy.</li><li>Hydroxyurea prevents recurrences of sickle cell crises by increasing hemoglobin F. Increase the dose of hydroxyurea until the hemoglobin F level rises above 10â15%. If WBC is low, do not increase the dose.</li></ul><p><br></p><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">TIPS</strong></p><ul><li>Sickle cell is caused by a point mutation at position <span style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">6 of the beta-globin chain:</span> Valine replaces glutamic acid.</li><li>Normal Adult Hemoglobin Electrophoresis showed -HBA 95-98%, HbA2-2-3% and HBF is less than 1-2%</li><li>Sickle cell Trait Hemoglobin electrophoresis(HBEP) showed-HBS 20-40 rest is HBA,HBA2 and HBS( Normally HBS is zero%)</li><li>Sickle cell disease HBEP-HBS 40-80% rest id HBA , HBA2 and HBF</li><li>Thalassemia Minor -HBEP has-HBA2 more than 5% rest is HBA and HBF(tey are asymptomatic, No treatment required), NO HBS</li><li>Thalassemia Major -HBEP has-HBF more than 90%, Rest is HBA and HBA2, NO HBS(diagnosed in childhood, RX is Lifelong blood transfusion and chelation with no cure. Bone marrow transplantation is the only curative treatment for Thalassemia Major</li></ul><p><br></p><h5><strong style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">Sickle Cell Trait</strong><span style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\"> </span></h5><h5>Sickle cell trait means the patient is heterozygous for the sickle gene (AS). The only manifestation of the sickle cell trait is a defect in the ability to concentrate the urine or âisosthenuria.â They are clinically asymptomatic and have both a normal CBC level and a normal smear result. Hematuria may sometimes occur. There is no treatment for sickle cell trait.</h5>.</p>"
