                  "__cdata": "<p class=\"p_20 black\">Correct!</p><p>Correct answer is B : Rhumatoidarthritis, Splenomegaly and low WBC count<br/><p>Felty's syndrome, also called Felty syndrome, (FS) is a rare autoimmune disease characterized by the triad of rheumatoid arthritis, enlargement of the spleen and too few neutrophils in the blood. The condition is more common in those aged 50â70 years, specifically more prevalent in females than males, and more so in Caucasians than those of African descent. It is a deforming disease that causes many complications for the individual. </p><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">Treatment</strong>-There is no real treatment for Felty's syndrome, rather the best method in the management of the disease is to control the underlying rheumatoid arthritis. Immunosuppressive therapy for RA often improves granulocytopenia and splenomegaly; this finding reflects the fact that Felty's syndrome is an immune-mediated disease. A major challenge in treating FS is a recurring infection caused by neutropenia. Therefore, in order to decide upon and begin treatment, the cause and relationship of neutropenia with the overall condition must be well understood.[8] Most of the traditional medications used to treat RA have been used in the treatment of Felty's syndrome. No well-conducted, randomized, controlled trials support the use of any single agent. Most reports on treatment regimens involve small numbers of patients. Splenectomy may improve neutropenia in severe disease. Use of rituximab and leflunomide have been proposed. Use of gold therapy has also been described.</p>.</p>"
